  "prompt": "Is it possible to live a relationship in an IIM like in the Two States book?",
  "response": "Yes, it's possible to have a relationship in an Indian Institute of Management (IIM) setting similar to what is portrayed in Chetan Bhagat's novel \"Two States.\" The book, which is semi-autobiographical, tells the story of two IIM Ahmedabad students from different cultural backgrounds who fall in love and navigate the challenges of convincing their families to accept their relationship.\n\nWhile the book's narrative is specific to its characters and their circumstances, the core elements\u2014meeting and forming a bond with someone from a different cultural or regional background, dealing with parental expectations, and balancing academic and personal lives\u2014are experiences that could be relatable to many students in such institutions. IIMs, like many educational institutions, bring together a diverse group of students from across India, offering opportunities for cross-cultural interactions and relationships. \n\nOf course, each person's experience will differ based on individual circumstances, personal values, and family dynamics. The challenges and outcomes of a relationship at an IIM (or any similar setting) would depend greatly on the people involved and how they choose to handle the situations they encounter.",
